values: these were all taken on day four but i'm separating them. just a few of dinner and the ship. dinner was all fancy 3 course meals but just before dessert the waitstaff would put on a small show and sing for everyone. it was very weird but the drunk people loved it.

Day four--our last day--was spent in key west. it seemed the hottest here. key west is a strange place, many streets lack stoplights and stop signs, there are also no crosswalks. i encountered many bongs, and there were plenty of bars including one featuring an elvis impersonator. we went to ripley's first which wasn't that exciting. then walked around mindlessly in the heat. there's lots of key lime paraphernalia. in a small "mall" we went into we were invited to watch some nature video which we went to for the free seats and air conditioning. it was a decent video until they got to the end and started quoting scripture at us. as we walked out some creepy lady with no expression gave us pamphlets with picture of birds telling us how to cope with stress using christ. they also had little business cards advertising their website about the end of the world, which--as always--was nigh. the picture of the lighthouse took away from the panicked urgency though. and a walk down the path of key west history brings us to....

day three was spent on a private island owned by Royal Carribean--Cococay. the beaches were kind of rocky and though the offered snorkeling there weren't any fish, only a planted ship wreck and airplane. a sting ray decided to hang around the shallow parts of our end of the beach and caused quite a commotion. it was a mildly relaxing day ending in sunburns.

day two was spent in Nassau, Bahamas. got up at the crack of dawn to take a long ferry to a small island called "blackbeard's beach". apparently everything toursity in the bahamas is named after blackbeard. we later went to a market where you are assaulted by sweaty merchants. nassau really wasn't very pretty per se, there was a lot of garbage and rusted trucks and whatnot lying around.

so, i went on a cruise this week and i took a lot of pictures. it was 4 days, day one being departure from miami. i was going to do commentary, but this has been a 3 hour process so i'm going to opt out. if you care that much ask me. maybe i'll edit it in laters.

good riddance to the year of funkiness. '07 is one I'm more than glad is over and done with. I can only hope that things improve from here, but the pessimist in me has tied up and gagged the optimist and I'm afraid there's still room for un-improvement. ringing in the new year with 8-12 inches of snow and 40 mph winds, let this not be a sign of things to come. 2008 ahoy.
